WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.339 --> 00:00:06.673
[alarm clock ticking]

2
00:00:08.967 --> 00:00:11.678
[alarm clock ringing]

3
00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:17.267
[sighs]

4
00:00:19.770 --> 00:00:21.980
[somber music playing]

5
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.074
Tired of searching for subtitles?
Ray generates them instantly: getray.app

6
00:00:45.254 --> 00:00:49.007
[handler] <i>Field intelligence report
reference number S/BF-22</i>

7
00:00:49.550 --> 00:00:51.510
<i>on new dissident group Zeta.</i>

8
00:00:51.593 --> 00:00:54.179
<i>Issued 8th of November 1963.</i>

9
00:00:55.806 --> 00:00:59.685
<i>First identified during Lacy-Zarubin
Cultural Exchange.</i>

10
00:00:59.768 --> 00:01:03.856
<i>Zeta members show incentive
to work against Soviet interests.</i>

11
00:01:04.690 --> 00:01:08.277
<i>Initial funding request approved
after asset Andrei Zaitsev</i>

12
00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:10.696
<i>recruited other disaffected musicians.</i>

13
00:01:11.655 --> 00:01:15.617
<i>Request continued support of group
as Zaitsev has developed system</i>

14
00:01:15.701 --> 00:01:18.662
<i>to smuggle banned musical works
by composers</i>

15
00:01:18.745 --> 00:01:23.250
<i>such as Denisov. Schnittke.
Gubaidulina out of USSR</i>

16
00:01:23.834 --> 00:01:27.004
<i>by way of hiding them
in the lining of instrument cases.</i>

17
00:01:27.796 --> 00:01:29.464
<i>Suggest continued surveillance.</i>

18
00:01:35.846 --> 00:01:40.142
<i>Field intelligence report
reference number S/BF-26.</i>

19
00:01:40.851 --> 00:01:43.270
<i>Issued 15th of May 1964.</i>

20
00:01:44.354 --> 00:01:47.274
<i>Pressures of dissident activity
appear to be taking a toll.</i>

21
00:01:48.317 --> 00:01:50.777
<i>Significant conflict has emerged
within the group.</i>

22
00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:55.908
<i>Zaitsev and romantic interest
Tanya Danilova frequently argue.</i>

23
00:01:56.825 --> 00:01:59.870
<i>There is concern that discord in group
will undermine mission.</i>

24
00:01:59.953 --> 00:02:02.414
<i>but suggest continued funding for now.</i>

25
00:02:31.652 --> 00:02:35.489
<i>Field intelligence report
reference number S/BF-32.</i>

26
00:02:36.156 --> 00:02:38.408
<i>Issued 10th of September 1964.</i>

27
00:02:38.951 --> 00:02:41.245
<i>New suitor of subject Danilova.</i>

28
00:02:42.037 --> 00:02:46.708
<i>Lieutenant Valentin Mironov.
pilot in the Soviet Air Force.</i>

29
00:02:47.292 --> 00:02:51.505
<i>In light of Washington's directive
seeking new assets in Soviet military</i>

30
00:02:51.588 --> 00:02:53.423
<i>there is an opportunity present.</i>

31
00:02:56.844 --> 00:03:00.764
<i>Mironov is unaware of
Danilova's illegal dissident activity.</i>

32
00:03:01.348 --> 00:03:03.350
<i>Request continued surveillance.</i>

33
00:03:05.394 --> 00:03:09.147
<i>Field intelligence report
reference number S/BF-40.</i>

34
00:03:09.231 --> 00:03:11.984
<i>Issued 24th of December 1964.</i>

35
00:03:12.776 --> 00:03:15.320
<i>Danilova and Mironov
relationship progressing.</i>

36
00:03:16.321 --> 00:03:20.242
<i>Source indicates Mironov being recruited
for Soviet space program.</i>

37
00:03:20.325 --> 00:03:22.160
<i>Continued surveillance a priority.</i>

38
00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:27.291
[shutter clicking]

39
00:03:27.374 --> 00:03:30.836
<i>Field intelligence report
reference number S/BF-45.</i>

40
00:03:30.919 --> 00:03:33.547
<i>Issued 15th of January 1965.</i>

41
00:03:34.214 --> 00:03:36.216
<i>Mironov engaged to Danilova.</i>

42
00:03:36.717 --> 00:03:40.012
<i>Wedding set for February.
before start of cosmonaut training.</i>

43
00:03:40.554 --> 00:03:43.432
<i>Danilova seems to have
ceased dissident activity.</i>

44
00:03:44.308 --> 00:03:46.935
[clicking continues]

45
00:03:54.318 --> 00:03:58.113
[handler] <i>Field intelligence report
reference number S/BF-51.</i>

46
00:03:58.197 --> 00:04:01.158
<i>Issued 28th of February 1965.</i>

47
00:04:01.241 --> 00:04:05.245
<i>Source indicates imminent move of
Tanya and Valya Mironov to Star City.</i>

48
00:04:06.038 --> 00:04:08.624
<i>Surveillance opportunities to become
extremely limited.</i>

49
00:04:09.124 --> 00:04:12.294
<i>Urgent request for direct contact
with subject Mironov.</i>

50
00:04:13.045 --> 00:04:16.005
<i>Will use wife's dissident past
to ensure cooperation.</i>

51
00:04:34.024 --> 00:04:35.192
Lovely day. isn't it?

52
00:04:36.109 --> 00:04:37.110
Yeah.

53
00:04:39.821 --> 00:04:41.657
Congratulations on the wedding.
by the way.

54
00:04:42.449 --> 00:04:43.700
How did you know I was married?

55
00:04:43.784 --> 00:04:46.453
- [bus brakes squeal]
- [speaking indistinctly]

56
00:04:47.287 --> 00:04:49.790
[inaudible]

57
00:05:00.217 --> 00:05:03.929
[handler] <i>Field intelligence report
reference number S/BF-53.</i>

58
00:05:04.012 --> 00:05:06.348
<i>Issued 1st of March 1965.</i>

59
00:05:07.015 --> 00:05:09.768
<i>New asset. cosmonaut Valya Mironov.</i>

60
00:05:10.435 --> 00:05:12.145
<i>Code name "Nikolay."</i>

61
00:05:15.858 --> 00:05:17.860
[theme song playing]

62
00:06:38.857 --> 00:06:40.025
Chief Designer.

63
00:06:51.995 --> 00:06:53.580
Out! All of you.

64
00:06:59.545 --> 00:07:01.964
[clears throat] Here we are.

65
00:07:03.215 --> 00:07:04.424
What is it?

66
00:07:05.050 --> 00:07:06.301
[Chief Designer] This is the culprit.

67
00:07:07.553 --> 00:07:08.804
I need a…

68
00:07:29.366 --> 00:07:30.951
Excellent craftsmanship.

69
00:07:32.536 --> 00:07:35.247
[Sergei] The circuitry.
it's the same as a signal amplifier.

70
00:07:35.330 --> 00:07:37.916
You'd find one in an old argon processor.

71
00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:39.793
It's… [stutters] Yes. look.

72
00:07:39.877 --> 00:07:42.379
That is a GT-104 transistor.

73
00:07:42.462 --> 00:07:44.882
It's very common in Soviet transmitters.

74
00:07:44.965 --> 00:07:46.049
It's Soviet?

75
00:07:47.301 --> 00:07:48.552
Yes.

76
00:07:49.928 --> 00:07:50.971
[Chief Designer] But this…

77
00:07:51.722 --> 00:07:54.474
this is not part
of the original technology.

78
00:07:54.558 --> 00:07:55.559
This is…

79
00:07:56.518 --> 00:07:57.811
this is added later.

80
00:07:59.271 --> 00:08:01.106
[Sergei] It's a micro transmitter.

81
00:08:01.190 --> 00:08:05.027
That's why it looked like interference.
but really it was just drawing power.

82
00:08:07.988 --> 00:08:09.489
So it wasn't sabotage.

83
00:08:11.366 --> 00:08:12.826
It was espionage.

84
00:08:17.206 --> 00:08:18.415
Thank you. Sergei.

85
00:08:19.666 --> 00:08:20.709
You can go now.

86
00:08:30.886 --> 00:08:33.179
Another one of my Eagles is dead.

87
00:08:33.263 --> 00:08:35.432
- What are you implying?
- I'm not implying anything.

88
00:08:35.515 --> 00:08:36.725
I'm telling you explicitly.

89
00:08:36.808 --> 00:08:40.854
I will not have any more deaths
on my watch because of your paranoia.

90
00:08:41.897 --> 00:08:43.190
It was a transmitter.

91
00:08:43.273 --> 00:08:45.984
Forcing me to reboot the system
was an overreaction.

92
00:08:46.068 --> 00:08:49.696
I made a decision based on
the information we had at the time.

93
00:08:49.780 --> 00:08:52.282
Our operations must remain secure.

94
00:08:52.366 --> 00:08:53.784
Not "we." Not "ours."

95
00:08:53.867 --> 00:08:55.827
My cosmonauts did the best they could.

96
00:08:55.911 --> 00:08:58.872
My systems would have functioned
without your interference.

97
00:08:58.956 --> 00:09:00.707
You didn't hold up your side.

98
00:09:00.791 --> 00:09:03.293
I wasn't aware we were on different sides.

99
00:09:03.877 --> 00:09:06.171
I handle the engineering.

100
00:09:06.255 --> 00:09:07.422
You handle security.

101
00:09:07.506 --> 00:09:09.967
What is the point of you
if you can't do that?

102
00:09:13.470 --> 00:09:15.389
I'm not taking the fall for your failures.

103
00:09:15.889 --> 00:09:17.349
Go and say that to Moscow.

104
00:09:54.803 --> 00:09:55.846
Excuse me.

105
00:10:00.142 --> 00:10:01.143
Excu…

106
00:10:01.977 --> 00:10:03.061
[door locks]

107
00:10:22.706 --> 00:10:23.957
[knocking]

108
00:10:25.918 --> 00:10:26.919
Hello?

109
00:10:35.969 --> 00:10:37.095
Comrade Chadha?

110
00:10:37.721 --> 00:10:38.722
From India?

111
00:10:39.348 --> 00:10:40.641
How did you guess?

112
00:10:44.061 --> 00:10:45.270
Your name's on the boxes.

113
00:10:54.488 --> 00:10:57.449
So. uh. how are you
settling in to Star City?

114
00:10:59.159 --> 00:11:00.994
Off to a great start.

115
00:11:01.078 --> 00:11:03.247
No one has told me
what I'm to be working on.

116
00:11:05.082 --> 00:11:07.584
This is normal.
Now we must get back to work.

117
00:11:19.054 --> 00:11:20.973
[Lakshmi]
Where's the rest of my equipment?

118
00:11:23.016 --> 00:11:25.686
[sighs] Do you know
where I could find the chief designer?

119
00:11:25.769 --> 00:11:28.146
I really feel like there
might have been a mix-up.

120
00:11:28.772 --> 00:11:30.649
[scoffs] Good luck with that.

121
00:11:30.732 --> 00:11:32.025
He's a very busy man.

122
00:11:57.676 --> 00:11:58.677
[in Hindi] Lakshmi…

123
00:11:59.428 --> 00:12:01.263
They're listening to us.

124
00:12:02.598 --> 00:12:04.016
You are being paranoid.

125
00:12:04.099 --> 00:12:06.143
I am not. [stammers]

126
00:12:06.226 --> 00:12:11.190
I was unpacking and yelling about
all the cursed flies in here and then

127
00:12:11.273 --> 00:12:12.983
after I get back from the market…

128
00:12:16.111 --> 00:12:17.112
I find this.

129
00:12:17.696 --> 00:12:18.906
It wasn't here before.

130
00:12:18.989 --> 00:12:21.658
I am telling you they must
have microphones in the walls.

131
00:12:22.618 --> 00:12:24.620
Do you think they have them
in the bathroom? Oh. goodness!

132
00:12:25.704 --> 00:12:26.747
[whispering] Bedroom?

133
00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:35.297
- [chuckles]
- [grunts]

134
00:12:36.423 --> 00:12:38.425
- [chuckles]
- You're laughing?

135
00:12:42.221 --> 00:12:43.847
We were warned about this.

136
00:12:43.931 --> 00:12:45.849
- We knew what to expect.
- No. Lakshmi.

137
00:12:46.892 --> 00:12:50.729
Hearing about Soviet surveillance
is very different than living it.

138
00:12:55.067 --> 00:12:56.777
Are you a spy. then?

139
00:12:56.860 --> 00:12:59.446
- No. Of course not.
- Then what is the problem. Manu?

140
00:13:01.615 --> 00:13:03.617
I'm the one who should be upset.

141
00:13:05.077 --> 00:13:08.372
[sighs] I thought this was my time.

142
00:13:08.455 --> 00:13:10.165
My chance to do something.

143
00:13:10.707 --> 00:13:13.502
They are doing the most
amazing things. but…

144
00:13:13.585 --> 00:13:16.630
You should see where they put me.

145
00:13:17.130 --> 00:13:18.841
- Why did they bring me here?
- Sorry.

146
00:13:19.842 --> 00:13:21.343
Sorry. my love.

147
00:13:23.762 --> 00:13:24.888
[in English] Sorry.

148
00:13:24.972 --> 00:13:26.515
[fly buzzing]

149
00:13:29.017 --> 00:13:30.269
[buzzing stops]

150
00:13:30.352 --> 00:13:31.937
[laughing]

151
00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:33.480
- [in Hindi] Got him.
- [laughs]

152
00:13:35.649 --> 00:13:38.527
- [Lakshmi speaking Hindi. chuckles]
- [Manu. in English] Sorry.

153
00:13:40.571 --> 00:13:43.073
[Lakshmi. Manu speaking Hindi]

154
00:13:43.156 --> 00:13:45.158
[in English]
Colonel Raskova wants to see you.

155
00:14:02.926 --> 00:14:04.261
Comrade Colonel?

156
00:14:04.344 --> 00:14:05.345
[Lyudmilla] Yes?

157
00:14:11.685 --> 00:14:15.480
I've been reviewing notations of any
suspicious activity after what happened.

158
00:14:15.564 --> 00:14:17.900
Even if it's just petty speculation.

159
00:14:19.193 --> 00:14:20.194
Irina Vasilievna.

160
00:14:20.277 --> 00:14:23.739
do you want to document petty speculation
for the rest of your life?

161
00:14:24.239 --> 00:14:25.407
No.

162
00:14:25.490 --> 00:14:26.742
I thought as much.

163
00:14:27.659 --> 00:14:29.661
Find someone to cover your assignments.

164
00:14:30.287 --> 00:14:33.332
I need this device traced.

165
00:14:33.415 --> 00:14:34.833
Quickly and quietly.

166
00:14:35.542 --> 00:14:37.294
Find out where it was manufactured.

167
00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:39.922
I want to know who ordered it.

168
00:14:40.464 --> 00:14:42.049
They could lead us to the mole.

169
00:14:42.633 --> 00:14:43.926
Find out what this is.

170
00:14:52.684 --> 00:14:53.727
Bring this with you.

171
00:15:00.484 --> 00:15:01.485
I don't need that.

172
00:15:01.985 --> 00:15:04.071
You go into the field alone.
you take a weapon.

173
00:15:08.158 --> 00:15:09.743
You received the training. yes?

174
00:15:10.536 --> 00:15:11.745
Yes.

175
00:15:13.997 --> 00:15:15.165
You can go.

176
00:15:34.184 --> 00:15:36.228
[classical music playing on record]

177
00:15:59.793 --> 00:16:02.546
[song continues]

178
00:16:28.572 --> 00:16:30.073
[song continues]

179
00:16:31.533 --> 00:16:32.659
[door opens]

180
00:16:34.161 --> 00:16:35.162
Hello?

181
00:16:41.001 --> 00:16:42.169
What are you doing home?

182
00:16:43.003 --> 00:16:46.131
[Valya] Training finished early.
I thought I'd eat something.

183
00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:54.181
Any mail? Anyone stop by?

184
00:16:55.432 --> 00:16:56.433
No.

185
00:16:58.310 --> 00:16:59.478
Why would they?

186
00:17:00.479 --> 00:17:02.189
What's wrong?
Why are you acting like this?

187
00:17:03.482 --> 00:17:05.150
[scoffs] "Like this"? Like what?

188
00:17:07.944 --> 00:17:09.655
[song continues]

189
00:17:17.996 --> 00:17:19.623
[record skipping]

190
00:17:31.301 --> 00:17:32.594
[song stops]

191
00:17:43.188 --> 00:17:44.189
[Valya] I'm sorry.

192
00:17:47.734 --> 00:17:50.112
I thought we had a really good night
in Moscow. didn't we?

193
00:17:54.157 --> 00:17:55.409
Did I do something wrong?

194
00:17:58.120 --> 00:17:59.121
Tell me.

195
00:18:06.003 --> 00:18:08.130
No. I'm just tired.

196
00:18:21.727 --> 00:18:22.728
[Sasha] <i>Arseni.</i>

197
00:18:24.146 --> 00:18:25.147
<i>Arseni.</i>

198
00:18:25.230 --> 00:18:26.231
[breathes heavily]

199
00:18:27.232 --> 00:18:28.650
[Sasha] <i>Arseni.</i>

200
00:18:28.734 --> 00:18:29.985
[gasps]

201
00:18:30.694 --> 00:18:32.112
[breathes heavily]

202
00:18:33.488 --> 00:18:34.489
[door opens]

203
00:18:36.366 --> 00:18:37.367
[door closes]

204
00:18:45.542 --> 00:18:46.627
[grunts]

205
00:18:48.295 --> 00:18:49.379
[sighs]

206
00:18:54.301 --> 00:18:58.222
MORE SPEECHES TODAY.
BACK TONIGHT. A.

207
00:19:10.150 --> 00:19:11.568
[sighs]

208
00:19:35.384 --> 00:19:36.385
[sniffs]

209
00:19:42.933 --> 00:19:45.143
[whispering]

210
00:19:50.691 --> 00:19:52.985
[Chief Designer] You must understand.
Mila Aleksandrovna.

211
00:19:53.068 --> 00:19:57.114
that all missions. training and otherwise.
are highly confidential.

212
00:19:57.948 --> 00:19:59.408
Here's. um…

213
00:20:00.617 --> 00:20:02.452
here's the letter he wrote you.

214
00:20:18.260 --> 00:20:19.887
My condolences.

215
00:20:22.222 --> 00:20:23.682
[sniffs. cries]

216
00:20:28.729 --> 00:20:29.813
[crying continues]

217
00:20:33.859 --> 00:20:37.529
Comrade Mironov trained him.
and Comrade Polivanov…

218
00:20:38.447 --> 00:20:39.823
was with him when he died.

219
00:20:39.907 --> 00:20:41.450
[breathes heavily]

220
00:20:42.409 --> 00:20:44.244
[Chief Designer] They're here for you now.

221
00:20:51.168 --> 00:20:53.253
He-He-He went the way
he would've wanted to.

222
00:20:58.300 --> 00:20:59.718
He wanted to come back.

223
00:21:02.387 --> 00:21:03.514
What happened?

224
00:21:10.938 --> 00:21:12.314
I-I don't wanna lie to you.

225
00:21:12.397 --> 00:21:13.607
Then don't.

226
00:21:18.195 --> 00:21:19.530
I didn't do enough.

227
00:21:20.197 --> 00:21:21.740
- It should've been me.
- [Valya] Sasha.

228
00:21:21.823 --> 00:21:23.325
Stop it. Stop. stop. stop.

229
00:21:23.408 --> 00:21:24.660
[Sasha] Sorry. [mutters]

230
00:21:26.912 --> 00:21:28.288
She doesn't need to hear that.

231
00:21:28.872 --> 00:21:29.957
You didn't kill him.

232
00:21:30.666 --> 00:21:31.708
I was the pilot.

233
00:21:31.792 --> 00:21:34.378
[inhales deeply]
I sent him into that compartment.

234
00:21:34.461 --> 00:21:35.963
Did you cause the interference?

235
00:21:39.508 --> 00:21:40.509
No.

236
00:21:41.677 --> 00:21:42.678
No.

237
00:21:43.929 --> 00:21:44.930
Up there…

238
00:21:46.557 --> 00:21:49.017
no one's responsible for anything

239
00:21:50.102 --> 00:21:51.520
besides their own survival.

240
00:21:59.361 --> 00:22:00.779
[whispering indistinctly]

241
00:22:11.498 --> 00:22:13.083
[Anastasia] <i>I remember it well.</i>

242
00:22:13.667 --> 00:22:17.004
The moment I had spent
my whole life working towards.

243
00:22:20.257 --> 00:22:25.387
I was chosen to serve my homeland
the only way I could.

244
00:22:26.180 --> 00:22:27.806
As a cosmonaut.

245
00:22:29.266 --> 00:22:30.434
As a woman.

246
00:22:32.144 --> 00:22:33.645
As a Soviet.

247
00:22:34.730 --> 00:22:39.526
I understood the cosmos
was not mine to conquer.

248
00:22:41.278 --> 00:22:43.238
It had always been ours.

249
00:23:03.592 --> 00:23:08.722
Well. thank you. Comrade Belikova.
for your service to your nation.

250
00:23:08.805 --> 00:23:11.808
And thank you to the
Committee for Soviet Women of Leningrad

251
00:23:11.892 --> 00:23:14.019
for hosting this wonderful event.

252
00:23:14.686 --> 00:23:18.023
The general secretary
is proud of your work.

253
00:23:22.611 --> 00:23:25.614
[Lyudmilla] What were your
responsibilities on <i>Luna 17?</i>

254
00:23:25.697 --> 00:23:29.660
Chief Designer had me analyzing the
propellant margins on the lunar lander.

255
00:23:31.578 --> 00:23:34.039
Did you ever notice
anything suspicious in the lab?

256
00:23:35.123 --> 00:23:39.086
I'm too busy to notice anything
except the circuits that I'm cutting.

257
00:23:42.130 --> 00:23:44.132
You signed off on the final boosters. yes?

258
00:23:45.092 --> 00:23:47.177
Ship shape. No issues.

259
00:23:48.554 --> 00:23:52.266
Did you see anyone tampering
with the train cars to Baikonur?

260
00:23:52.349 --> 00:23:53.600
Absolutely not.

261
00:23:54.184 --> 00:23:55.602
We left at 2100.

262
00:23:55.686 --> 00:23:57.354
There was no one on the premises.

263
00:24:00.232 --> 00:24:05.195
Who else might have had access
to the descent module before launch?

264
00:24:05.279 --> 00:24:06.280
No one.

265
00:24:07.698 --> 00:24:09.616
besides the launch engineers and the crew.

266
00:24:10.659 --> 00:24:11.827
Maybe the trainers.

267
00:24:13.996 --> 00:24:15.956
Thank you for your cooperation.

268
00:24:17.082 --> 00:24:18.208
You can go.

269
00:24:25.757 --> 00:24:29.469
[Lyudmilla] <i>Yes. I'm making
excellent progress. Comrade Director.</i>

270
00:24:29.553 --> 00:24:31.763
[Konstantin] <i>I think you should come
to headquarters in Moscow</i>

271
00:24:31.847 --> 00:24:35.184
<i>and update us in person
on how this breach was possible.</i>

272
00:24:36.059 --> 00:24:39.354
Uh. well. my investigation is progressing.

273
00:24:39.438 --> 00:24:40.939
I have it under control.

274
00:24:41.815 --> 00:24:44.234
<i>I'm sure you do. but come anyway.</i>

275
00:24:45.819 --> 00:24:46.904
Thank you. comrade.

276
00:24:46.987 --> 00:24:48.488
I will come in tomorrow.

277
00:24:57.915 --> 00:24:59.708
[party member] I've filed seven requests

278
00:24:59.791 --> 00:25:05.005
to get Belikova to make an appearance
at the factory next month. but nothing.

279
00:25:05.088 --> 00:25:08.133
[Maxim] Oh. well. persistence is
a virtue. comrade.

280
00:25:09.843 --> 00:25:11.887
It's because she's going back
to the moon again. isn't she?

281
00:25:11.970 --> 00:25:12.971
Oh. no. no. no.

282
00:25:13.055 --> 00:25:15.390
The state can't risk that.
She's much too valuable.

283
00:25:15.474 --> 00:25:18.810
[chuckles] Yeah.
but you mean too valuable to you?

284
00:25:20.521 --> 00:25:22.439
[Maxim] Now. Be careful.

285
00:25:22.523 --> 00:25:24.650
[both chuckling]

286
00:25:44.545 --> 00:25:46.338
How long to the next appearance?

287
00:25:48.382 --> 00:25:49.508
Just an hour.

288
00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:56.515
Here.

289
00:25:57.516 --> 00:25:58.517
No.

290
00:26:04.606 --> 00:26:06.441
You were with Gagarin. weren't you?

291
00:26:08.902 --> 00:26:09.903
Mm-hmm.

292
00:26:11.613 --> 00:26:13.031
[Anastasia] When did he know?

293
00:26:15.033 --> 00:26:16.034
Know what?

294
00:26:18.203 --> 00:26:20.038
That he would never go back up again.

295
00:26:24.001 --> 00:26:25.711
Not long after his world tour.

296
00:26:45.856 --> 00:26:47.024
Give me that.

297
00:26:54.823 --> 00:26:56.033
[knocking on door]

298
00:27:06.043 --> 00:27:07.044
[grunts]

299
00:27:12.841 --> 00:27:14.009
Welcome back.

300
00:27:15.552 --> 00:27:16.678
How was the training mission?

301
00:27:18.180 --> 00:27:19.181
[clicks tongue]

302
00:27:21.475 --> 00:27:23.435
- Can I come in?
- I haven't cleaned. really.

303
00:27:31.985 --> 00:27:33.403
So who sleeps in the bedroom?

304
00:27:33.487 --> 00:27:34.488
[chuckles]

305
00:27:35.822 --> 00:27:37.115
She does.

306
00:27:37.199 --> 00:27:38.534
And who cooks dinner?

307
00:27:39.701 --> 00:27:41.370
Is this what you came here to talk about?

308
00:27:41.453 --> 00:27:42.454
No.

309
00:27:49.044 --> 00:27:50.462
I saw him with a woman.

310
00:27:52.965 --> 00:27:54.132
Who?

311
00:27:55.133 --> 00:27:56.385
Valya.

312
00:27:57.469 --> 00:27:58.470
[snorts]

313
00:28:00.389 --> 00:28:01.431
His mother?

314
00:28:02.724 --> 00:28:03.809
I'm being serious.

315
00:28:05.227 --> 00:28:07.020
I'm sorry.
You think Valya is having an affair?

316
00:28:07.104 --> 00:28:08.564
I don't know what I think.

317
00:28:08.647 --> 00:28:11.650
All I know is I saw him
and some woman at the concert hall.

318
00:28:12.317 --> 00:28:14.069
I don't know how to explain it. It…

319
00:28:14.152 --> 00:28:16.530
It felt intimate.
like they knew each other well.

320
00:28:21.743 --> 00:28:23.412
He's not having an affair. Tanya.

321
00:28:27.958 --> 00:28:29.459
I wish he'd have an affair.

322
00:28:30.586 --> 00:28:32.171
It'd be good for him. [chuckles]

323
00:28:32.754 --> 00:28:33.755
Fuck you.

324
00:28:33.839 --> 00:28:34.840
[clicks tongue]

325
00:28:35.549 --> 00:28:36.842
You jealous?

326
00:28:36.925 --> 00:28:37.926
No. I…

327
00:28:39.386 --> 00:28:40.679
I don't know.

328
00:28:46.059 --> 00:28:47.352
[exhales]

329
00:29:19.968 --> 00:29:21.553
[clanking]

330
00:29:23.972 --> 00:29:25.140
[clanking continues]

331
00:29:30.312 --> 00:29:32.731
[clanking continues]

332
00:29:52.584 --> 00:29:53.919
[clanking continues]

333
00:30:30.247 --> 00:30:31.498
What is this place?

334
00:30:32.666 --> 00:30:34.042
Hand me the wrench. will you?

335
00:30:36.587 --> 00:30:37.880
Sorry about the noise.

336
00:30:39.715 --> 00:30:40.966
I don't sleep much.

337
00:30:42.759 --> 00:30:45.429
So you've been relegated
to the fringes too? [chuckles]

338
00:30:46.722 --> 00:30:48.098
Something like that.

339
00:30:51.810 --> 00:30:54.021
You know. when I was told I was being
assigned to Star City.

340
00:30:54.104 --> 00:30:58.233
I thought I'd be at the forefront
of space travel. but instead I'm…

341
00:30:59.401 --> 00:31:01.195
here. [chuckles]

342
00:31:01.278 --> 00:31:02.738
Pushed aside. huh?

343
00:31:06.158 --> 00:31:08.493
Don't underestimate yourself. comrade.

344
00:31:09.453 --> 00:31:13.540
Your work on self-sustaining generation
of breathable air

345
00:31:14.583 --> 00:31:16.293
is the future of space travel.

346
00:31:18.795 --> 00:31:19.922
You know my work?

347
00:31:20.005 --> 00:31:21.131
Of course.

348
00:31:22.132 --> 00:31:26.762
It's the final piece required
to truly conquer the cosmos.

349
00:31:31.850 --> 00:31:34.895
You know. if they had used my
BIOS system to generate oxygen

350
00:31:34.978 --> 00:31:38.524
instead of <i>Luna 17's</i>
inefficient LiOH and O2 tanks.

351
00:31:38.607 --> 00:31:41.360
it would've saved 77 kilograms.

352
00:31:42.319 --> 00:31:44.821
[scoffs] No offense
to whoever designed it.

353
00:31:46.615 --> 00:31:47.824
No offense taken.

354
00:31:55.374 --> 00:31:56.834
You're him. [chuckles]

355
00:31:58.335 --> 00:32:00.254
You're the chief designer?

356
00:32:00.796 --> 00:32:02.714
Apologies for the ruse.

357
00:32:02.798 --> 00:32:05.968
I didn't bring you here to get us
to the moon. Comrade Chadha.

358
00:32:07.302 --> 00:32:09.680
- [chuckles]
- We've already been to the moon.

359
00:32:22.568 --> 00:32:24.111
- You're going to Venus?
- No.

360
00:32:25.028 --> 00:32:27.197
We are going to Venus.

361
00:32:30.200 --> 00:32:31.535
[Lakshmi] My lab equipment.

362
00:32:40.419 --> 00:32:42.129
And you're gonna help us get there.

363
00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:55.267
- Hello.
- [employee] Can I help you?

364
00:32:55.350 --> 00:32:56.852
I'm looking for head office.

365
00:32:56.935 --> 00:32:58.854
Ah. yes. You enter there.

366
00:33:13.744 --> 00:33:14.995
[door opens]

367
00:33:26.548 --> 00:33:27.549
What do you want?

368
00:33:33.514 --> 00:33:35.724
Do you recognize this?

369
00:33:35.807 --> 00:33:36.892
Of course.

370
00:33:37.434 --> 00:33:38.602
It's one of our transmitters.

371
00:33:42.814 --> 00:33:44.942
Do you know who might
have acquired it from you?

372
00:33:48.195 --> 00:33:50.822
Well. that's hard to say.
We make a number of them each day.

373
00:33:54.952 --> 00:33:57.204
To keep such a pace must be difficult.

374
00:33:58.413 --> 00:34:00.499
I'm sure regulations get in the way.

375
00:34:02.084 --> 00:34:04.962
In fact. I noted
multiple violations on my way in.

376
00:34:06.463 --> 00:34:08.757
There could be serious repercussions
for such infractions.

377
00:34:08.841 --> 00:34:11.885
- We're just trying to meet our quotas.
- I'm just trying to do my job. comrade.

378
00:34:17.099 --> 00:34:18.308
Please take another look.

379
00:34:27.192 --> 00:34:29.069
This is our standard transmitter.

380
00:34:30.529 --> 00:34:31.780
You see here?

381
00:34:33.197 --> 00:34:34.449
It's been modified…

382
00:34:36.118 --> 00:34:38.078
- with this.
- Yeah. I wanted to ask about that.

383
00:34:38.161 --> 00:34:40.455
It must have been added later
by whoever purchased it.

384
00:34:40.539 --> 00:34:42.040
It's certainly not Soviet.

385
00:34:42.875 --> 00:34:43.876
How can you tell?

386
00:34:45.460 --> 00:34:46.670
It's an unusual alloy.

387
00:34:47.212 --> 00:34:48.964
Not something we use. Let me test it.

388
00:34:58.223 --> 00:34:59.641
Look at the meter.

389
00:34:59.725 --> 00:35:02.436
When I touch the probes.
look at how much it can…

390
00:35:03.604 --> 00:35:04.605
Where did you get this?

391
00:35:05.731 --> 00:35:07.149
I've never seen anything like it.

392
00:35:09.026 --> 00:35:11.612
It's not available anywhere
in the Soviet Union.

393
00:35:12.446 --> 00:35:13.822
It must have been smuggled in.

394
00:35:13.906 --> 00:35:16.658
This is four times
the thermal conductivity of copper.

395
00:35:18.118 --> 00:35:20.704
[inhales sharply]
What might it have been added for?

396
00:35:20.787 --> 00:35:23.457
Well. with this.
you have got an incredible heat sink.

397
00:35:24.625 --> 00:35:28.504
Which means this tiny transmitter can have
a lot of energy flowing through it

398
00:35:28.587 --> 00:35:30.297
and still be able to function.

399
00:35:30.964 --> 00:35:35.260
Uh. this could handle a power supply
several times our standard size.

400
00:35:37.429 --> 00:35:39.598
What was the transmitter's power source?

401
00:35:41.266 --> 00:35:43.393
I'd like to see your purchasing records.

402
00:36:08.126 --> 00:36:09.127
[Konstantin] Come in.

403
00:36:17.761 --> 00:36:19.304
Lyudmilla Efimovna.

404
00:36:19.388 --> 00:36:20.472
[Lyudmilla] Kostya.

405
00:36:22.391 --> 00:36:24.601
I wish we were meeting
under better circumstances.

406
00:36:26.061 --> 00:36:27.187
[clears throat] Thank you.

407
00:36:27.271 --> 00:36:31.942
I have contained the breach
and located the device from the craft.

408
00:36:32.025 --> 00:36:35.320
The search for
who planted it is progressing.

409
00:36:38.657 --> 00:36:40.993
This is Radimir Sergeievich Petrovsky.

410
00:36:42.786 --> 00:36:44.121
Your new lieutenant?

411
00:36:44.204 --> 00:36:46.999
The new first deputy
of the Second Chief Directorate.

412
00:36:51.128 --> 00:36:52.504
First deputy.

413
00:36:53.964 --> 00:36:55.465
My mother worked in your bullpen.

414
00:36:56.300 --> 00:36:57.467
Raya Famova.

415
00:36:58.552 --> 00:36:59.678
Do you remember her?

416
00:37:00.345 --> 00:37:02.347
It's unfortunate
she had to retire so early.

417
00:37:02.431 --> 00:37:03.932
Hmm. She raised a family.

418
00:37:04.558 --> 00:37:07.978
Sorry. are we here to talk
about your mother or about <i>Luna 17</i>?

419
00:37:08.061 --> 00:37:09.563
[Konstantin. Lyudmilla chuckle]

420
00:37:10.898 --> 00:37:12.524
We're going to need a full report

421
00:37:12.608 --> 00:37:15.777
on how the Americans managed
to perform this stunning infiltration.

422
00:37:15.861 --> 00:37:17.154
It's very troubling.

423
00:37:17.237 --> 00:37:18.572
I will find out what happened.

424
00:37:18.655 --> 00:37:20.741
but please don't waste my time
with reports.

425
00:37:20.824 --> 00:37:23.285
It's just a lot of paperwork
that no one's going to read.

426
00:37:23.368 --> 00:37:24.995
Oh. I can assure you it will be read.

427
00:37:27.039 --> 00:37:28.040
[Konstantin] Lyudmilla.

428
00:37:28.749 --> 00:37:31.168
everyone appreciates
your decades of service.

429
00:37:31.251 --> 00:37:33.337
But this is how it's done now.

430
00:37:36.798 --> 00:37:40.552
A senior cosmonaut was executed
under your watch.

431
00:37:40.636 --> 00:37:43.222
- Uh. Yana--
- Akhmatova.

432
00:37:43.889 --> 00:37:47.726
Yes. She admitted to being
co-opted by the Americans.

433
00:37:47.809 --> 00:37:50.103
It now appears
that she wasn't working alone.

434
00:37:50.187 --> 00:37:52.773
It's a larger operation
than we first suspected.

435
00:37:55.108 --> 00:37:58.070
Radimir will be happy to lend the help
of the Second Chief Directorate.

436
00:37:58.153 --> 00:38:01.406
He has a particular interest
in the space program.

437
00:38:01.990 --> 00:38:04.326
I studied electronic engineering
at university

438
00:38:04.409 --> 00:38:06.286
before I joined the security service.

439
00:38:06.370 --> 00:38:09.915
That's nice.
but it's nothing I can't handle.

440
00:38:14.294 --> 00:38:19.216
And you'll also need to document what led
to the death of cosmonaut Arseni Vetrov.

441
00:38:19.967 --> 00:38:22.553
whether technical failure
or due to the security breach.

442
00:38:22.636 --> 00:38:24.555
And then we can decide how to…

443
00:38:25.681 --> 00:38:26.682
move on.

444
00:38:26.765 --> 00:38:28.225
Should I be concerned?

445
00:38:29.518 --> 00:38:30.644
[Konstantin] Of course not.

446
00:38:30.727 --> 00:38:33.522
You're a hero of the Soviet Union.
Comrade Raskova.

447
00:38:35.524 --> 00:38:36.817
Sounds like an obituary.

448
00:38:37.359 --> 00:38:38.569
No.

449
00:38:39.152 --> 00:38:40.821
It's a testament to your service.

450
00:38:43.615 --> 00:38:45.409
I will contain this.

451
00:38:45.492 --> 00:38:46.660
I can assure you.

452
00:38:50.289 --> 00:38:51.290
Good.

453
00:38:51.790 --> 00:38:53.041
See that you do.

454
00:39:01.425 --> 00:39:04.219
[speaking indistinctly]

455
00:39:04.303 --> 00:39:05.554
Walk with me.

456
00:39:09.141 --> 00:39:12.895
So what's the latest in the preparations
for the unmanned probe this week?

457
00:39:12.978 --> 00:39:15.772
Nearly all of the modules
have been transported

458
00:39:15.856 --> 00:39:20.360
and the N-1 is being moved to a pad
in Baikonur as we speak.

459
00:39:20.944 --> 00:39:23.906
Chief Designer.
everything is still on track.

460
00:39:24.615 --> 00:39:26.658
And now that Comrade Chadha is here.

461
00:39:26.742 --> 00:39:29.786
her life support systems
are functioning surprisingly well

462
00:39:29.870 --> 00:39:32.247
- and we'll be ready for launch.
- Good.

463
00:39:32.331 --> 00:39:35.876
Though with everything going on.
I wonder if…

464
00:39:35.959 --> 00:39:38.670
if it would be prudent
to postpone the launch until--

465
00:39:38.754 --> 00:39:40.214
It has to be now. Sergei.

466
00:39:40.297 --> 00:39:41.715
Or it will never happen.

467
00:39:41.798 --> 00:39:44.551
Yeah. Well. then we should discuss further
who will be assigned to the mission.

468
00:39:45.135 --> 00:39:46.637
[Chief Designer] I have that handled.

469
00:39:54.645 --> 00:39:56.146
Chief tell you why we're here?

470
00:40:00.567 --> 00:40:02.569
- [door opens. closes]
- [footsteps approaching]

471
00:40:09.618 --> 00:40:10.702
Do you need something?

472
00:40:12.913 --> 00:40:13.914
No.

473
00:40:14.748 --> 00:40:16.291
- Do you?
- [scoffs]

474
00:40:17.835 --> 00:40:19.837
[footsteps approaching]

475
00:40:28.470 --> 00:40:29.555
Sit down. please.

476
00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:33.433
Good.

477
00:40:34.434 --> 00:40:37.688
I have a craft set to launch
in three days' time.

478
00:40:37.771 --> 00:40:39.565
and she's in need of a crew.

479
00:40:43.694 --> 00:40:46.238
Due to the highly confidential nature
of the mission.

480
00:40:46.321 --> 00:40:47.948
no more notice was possible.

481
00:40:51.410 --> 00:40:53.579
You know me. Chief. I'm up for anything.

482
00:40:55.163 --> 00:40:58.250
But Colonel Raskova's grounded me
and Sasha after <i>Luna 17</i>.

483
00:40:58.333 --> 00:41:01.503
Which makes you perfect for
a mission no one can know about.

484
00:41:03.922 --> 00:41:06.341
- Where we going?
- I can't tell you till you agree to go.

485
00:41:06.425 --> 00:41:07.759
[chuckles]

486
00:41:11.054 --> 00:41:13.223
You can't tell anyone.
not even your spouses.

487
00:41:14.766 --> 00:41:16.476
You'll be gone for nine months.

488
00:41:18.312 --> 00:41:20.189
You have the night to think it over.

489
00:41:20.272 --> 00:41:21.523
[Pavel] Don't need the night.

490
00:41:22.524 --> 00:41:23.984
- I'm in.
- Good.

491
00:41:27.529 --> 00:41:29.948
You are going to use
my life support systems?

492
00:41:30.574 --> 00:41:31.658
Am I to train them on it?

493
00:41:31.742 --> 00:41:34.953
There's not enough time to train them
in something so complex.

494
00:41:35.037 --> 00:41:36.413
We couldn't even get the chlorella

495
00:41:36.496 --> 00:41:38.790
to metabolize enough carbon dioxide
till you arrived.

496
00:41:38.874 --> 00:41:39.875
No.

497
00:41:39.958 --> 00:41:41.126
You'll have to go with them.

498
00:41:43.504 --> 00:41:45.005
But I'm not a cosmonaut.

499
00:41:45.088 --> 00:41:46.173
Well. you are now.

500
00:41:47.841 --> 00:41:49.092
[scoffs]

501
00:41:49.176 --> 00:41:51.011
W-Wait. her?

502
00:41:51.803 --> 00:41:53.305
You must be joking.

503
00:41:53.889 --> 00:41:54.973
Especially her.

504
00:42:05.943 --> 00:42:07.110
I'm sorry. Chief.

505
00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:20.249
[Chief Designer]
My boy. I know you're struggling.

506
00:42:20.332 --> 00:42:22.543
but the only way to overcome this
is to keep going.

507
00:42:22.626 --> 00:42:24.920
You know as well as I do.
I should never be let near another ship.

508
00:42:25.003 --> 00:42:27.381
If you don't now. I worry you never will.

509
00:42:28.173 --> 00:42:29.591
Well. maybe that's a good thing.

510
00:42:32.970 --> 00:42:33.971
I'll resign.

511
00:42:34.638 --> 00:42:35.681
That makes things easier.

512
00:42:35.764 --> 00:42:38.600
You think I pulled you out
of the Air Force to make things easier?

513
00:42:39.309 --> 00:42:40.310
Hmm?

514
00:42:41.770 --> 00:42:43.355
I brought you here
even though they warned me

515
00:42:43.438 --> 00:42:45.858
that you were uncontrollable
and impulsive.

516
00:42:47.818 --> 00:42:49.820
There's no map to this mission.
We're drawing it.

517
00:42:49.903 --> 00:42:53.907
And I need a good pilot with impulses
that shouldn't be controlled.

518
00:42:53.991 --> 00:42:55.284
[scoffs]

519
00:42:55.367 --> 00:42:57.452
No. I-I can't take…

520
00:42:58.662 --> 00:43:00.998
any more lives in my hands.

521
00:43:01.748 --> 00:43:02.749
Don't you understand?

522
00:43:02.833 --> 00:43:07.254
Arseni Vetrov would never forgive you
for using his memory as an excuse. Sasha.

523
00:43:10.424 --> 00:43:13.468
He has no more missions.
You owe it to him to keep going.

524
00:43:17.264 --> 00:43:18.515
You owe it to yourself.

525
00:43:34.656 --> 00:43:36.867
[sniffs. sighs]

526
00:43:39.494 --> 00:43:42.456
[Anastasia] <i>Collective achievement
is the Soviet ideal.</i>

527
00:43:44.583 --> 00:43:45.751
There you go.

528
00:43:47.211 --> 00:43:48.587
There you go.

529
00:43:50.756 --> 00:43:52.257
Do you have any questions for me?

530
00:43:52.925 --> 00:43:54.259
No geometry questions though.

531
00:43:54.343 --> 00:43:55.552
I was never very good at that.

532
00:43:55.636 --> 00:43:57.804
Never won a gold medal in mathematics.

533
00:43:57.888 --> 00:43:58.889
Just silver.

534
00:43:59.473 --> 00:44:00.891
But even still.

535
00:44:01.642 --> 00:44:04.019
tried as hard as I could. and…

536
00:44:04.603 --> 00:44:06.271
and that's… that's it really.

537
00:44:06.355 --> 00:44:08.148
That's the… the secret. It's…

538
00:44:08.857 --> 00:44:11.068
You just never give up. so…

539
00:44:12.027 --> 00:44:13.820
Do you think we will get to go to space?

540
00:44:19.243 --> 00:44:20.494
Sooner you than me.

541
00:44:23.539 --> 00:44:25.290
Thank Comrade Belikova for her time.

542
00:44:25.374 --> 00:44:26.583
She's a very busy woman.

543
00:44:27.376 --> 00:44:28.961
- Thank you.
- [chuckles]

544
00:44:29.044 --> 00:44:30.379
[Slava] Okay. Thank you. girls.

545
00:44:35.843 --> 00:44:36.927
I'm starving.

546
00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:39.471
- You think there's anything to--
- I. uh… Please. allow me.

547
00:44:39.555 --> 00:44:41.098
Uh. it's on the math department.

548
00:44:41.181 --> 00:44:43.392
- No. it's all right.
- No. uh. just give me one second.

549
00:44:43.475 --> 00:44:44.476
[clears throat]

550
00:44:50.190 --> 00:44:51.400
He likes you.

551
00:44:52.818 --> 00:44:54.486
He doesn't know anything about me.

552
00:44:55.279 --> 00:44:56.947
Well. that never stopped anyone.

553
00:44:58.073 --> 00:44:59.074
[chuckles]

554
00:44:59.908 --> 00:45:05.414
Uh. we-we cannot have you eating
cafeteria food. Comrade Belikova. so…

555
00:45:06.206 --> 00:45:09.042
Please enjoy.
Courtesy of the physics faculty.

556
00:45:20.929 --> 00:45:23.015
Will you stop looking at me like that?

557
00:45:23.098 --> 00:45:24.725
[stammering]

558
00:45:24.808 --> 00:45:26.727
[clears throat. chuckles]

559
00:45:26.810 --> 00:45:28.937
I mean. I'm just so glad
that you're here. Comrade Belikova.

560
00:45:29.021 --> 00:45:30.856
Your achievements…

561
00:45:30.939 --> 00:45:33.483
[stammers]
It's been an inspiration to us all.

562
00:45:33.567 --> 00:45:34.902
It really has.

563
00:45:34.985 --> 00:45:38.572
Well. I promise you
that I'm just a hungry farm girl

564
00:45:38.655 --> 00:45:40.616
who followed orders
all the way to the moon.

565
00:45:41.158 --> 00:45:43.076
Well. I mean. you're-you're
so much more than that.

566
00:45:43.160 --> 00:45:44.411
[all chuckle]

567
00:45:44.494 --> 00:45:45.704
[Slava] You're a…

568
00:45:45.787 --> 00:45:47.581
You're a promise of something better.

569
00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:51.251
I don't know about that.

570
00:45:52.169 --> 00:45:55.214
I mean. honestly. I would give anything

571
00:45:55.297 --> 00:45:58.133
just to go somewhere
where no one knows who I am.

572
00:45:58.717 --> 00:46:03.680
And I would just eat
fresh tomatoes. and. like…

573
00:46:04.431 --> 00:46:07.935
[chuckles] …look up
at the constellations like I would

574
00:46:09.019 --> 00:46:12.940
when no one thought I could do
anything except milk a cow.

575
00:46:14.274 --> 00:46:16.360
Which I can. very well.

576
00:46:17.778 --> 00:46:18.779
[stammers]

577
00:46:23.784 --> 00:46:25.994
My dacha's 20 minutes from here.

578
00:46:27.162 --> 00:46:29.540
You can see more stars there
than you've ever seen in your whole life.

579
00:46:29.623 --> 00:46:30.749
[chuckles] Well. maybe not you.

580
00:46:30.832 --> 00:46:32.751
- [stammers. chuckles]
- [chuckles]

581
00:46:32.835 --> 00:46:34.503
[chuckles]

582
00:46:34.586 --> 00:46:35.921
There might even be a cow.

583
00:46:40.008 --> 00:46:41.927
[chuckles] It would be an honor.

584
00:46:44.847 --> 00:46:46.014
[chuckles]

585
00:46:48.267 --> 00:46:49.893
Well. are you sure about the cow?

586
00:46:51.103 --> 00:46:52.437
It might be a goat.

587
00:46:56.984 --> 00:46:57.985
[softly] I see.

588
00:46:59.278 --> 00:47:01.780
Well. I mean.
there's only one way to find out. no?

589
00:47:03.407 --> 00:47:05.659
- [chuckles]
- Yes? Yeah? Let's do it.

590
00:47:05.742 --> 00:47:07.661
- Yeah.
- I like goats too.

591
00:47:07.744 --> 00:47:10.247
- I mean. come on. let's go.
- Let's go. Okay!

592
00:47:10.330 --> 00:47:11.540
[Anastasia laughs]

593
00:48:19.983 --> 00:48:21.235
[rustling]

594
00:48:24.988 --> 00:48:26.156
Hello?

595
00:48:48.262 --> 00:48:49.721
[rustling continues]

596
00:49:12.786 --> 00:49:13.787
[gasps]

597
00:49:15.247 --> 00:49:16.999
Stop! Stop!

598
00:49:26.758 --> 00:49:29.219
[grunting. panting]

599
00:49:33.765 --> 00:49:35.142
[door opens. closes]

600
00:49:36.435 --> 00:49:37.728
[panting]

601
00:50:18.977 --> 00:50:21.104
[cheering]

602
00:50:22.940 --> 00:50:24.566
Yes!

603
00:50:25.776 --> 00:50:26.902
Yes!

604
00:50:31.406 --> 00:50:32.449
[shouts]

605
00:50:32.533 --> 00:50:34.368
- Okay! Here we go.
- Next one!

606
00:50:34.451 --> 00:50:36.286
- [vocalizing]
- Next one.

607
00:50:42.251 --> 00:50:43.252
Okay.

608
00:50:44.127 --> 00:50:46.213
- Yeah. yeah.
- Lovely. lovely. lovely. lovely!

609
00:50:46.296 --> 00:50:48.298
[all] Three. two. one.

610
00:50:48.382 --> 00:50:49.716
[laughs]

611
00:50:49.800 --> 00:50:51.093
[all cheer]

612
00:50:51.176 --> 00:50:52.219
Oh. my gosh!

613
00:50:52.302 --> 00:50:53.679
- [laughing]
- Yeah.

614
00:50:53.762 --> 00:50:55.180
[vehicle approaching]

615
00:50:55.264 --> 00:50:57.474
- [Anastasia] How far did that one go?
- [laughing]

616
00:50:57.558 --> 00:50:59.226
[Slava] Thirty meters at least.

617
00:50:59.309 --> 00:51:03.021
[all chattering. laughing]

618
00:51:03.105 --> 00:51:05.440
- [clears throat]
- [laughs] Uh-oh.

619
00:51:07.234 --> 00:51:08.235
Wh-Who is that?

620
00:51:08.318 --> 00:51:09.319
[Anastasia groans]

621
00:51:09.862 --> 00:51:12.197
[laughs] It's my husband.

622
00:51:12.281 --> 00:51:13.365
- [laughing]
- Oh.

623
00:51:13.448 --> 00:51:15.325
- Oh.
- [chuckles] Welcome!

624
00:51:15.409 --> 00:51:16.451
Welcome!

625
00:51:16.535 --> 00:51:17.703
Thank you for the call.

626
00:51:18.871 --> 00:51:20.080
Come! Come!

627
00:51:20.163 --> 00:51:21.623
[laughs] Hello!

628
00:51:22.416 --> 00:51:23.917
- Come.
- You can launch this one.

629
00:51:24.001 --> 00:51:25.586
- Hello!
- [pants] Welcome.

630
00:51:25.669 --> 00:51:26.712
Sasha.

631
00:51:28.630 --> 00:51:31.258
- Come in. The water's amazing.
- Get in the car. We're going home.

632
00:51:31.341 --> 00:51:32.843
[groaning]

633
00:51:33.802 --> 00:51:35.304
No! No. come in.

634
00:51:35.387 --> 00:51:36.388
- Come in.
- Get in the car.

635
00:51:36.471 --> 00:51:38.098
- Sasha. Sasha!
- We'll launch in your honor.

636
00:51:38.182 --> 00:51:39.349
- Yes. in your honor!
- My honor!

637
00:51:39.433 --> 00:51:40.434
[both shout]

638
00:51:41.518 --> 00:51:44.062
Here we go. Here we go!

639
00:51:44.146 --> 00:51:45.147
Get in the car.

640
00:51:45.230 --> 00:51:46.398
Gosh. you are no fun.

641
00:51:46.982 --> 00:51:48.775
- You're no fun.
- [teachers whooping]

642
00:51:54.156 --> 00:51:55.574
Yeah!

643
00:51:55.657 --> 00:51:58.035
- Whoo!
- Yes!

644
00:52:17.429 --> 00:52:18.472
[Sasha] No.

645
00:52:19.556 --> 00:52:20.557
Off my bed. You stink.

646
00:52:21.266 --> 00:52:23.602
- I need to shower.
- Yeah. I'm having one first.

647
00:52:23.685 --> 00:52:25.103
I was just in a lake.

648
00:52:25.187 --> 00:52:26.522
Yeah. whose fault was that?

649
00:52:27.231 --> 00:52:28.649
What are you saying?

650
00:52:29.274 --> 00:52:30.776
It's not subtle. what I'm saying.

651
00:52:31.443 --> 00:52:34.029
Because I've just been in a car all night
playing a dutiful husband

652
00:52:34.112 --> 00:52:37.032
while you drag half the physics department
into some fucking water.

653
00:52:37.115 --> 00:52:38.992
Hey! Don't you dare.

654
00:52:39.076 --> 00:52:42.913
If they won't let me fucking fly again.
why can't I try and enjoy myself?

655
00:52:43.497 --> 00:52:46.208
Since when were you opposed
to having a little fun. huh?

656
00:52:46.291 --> 00:52:48.919
Or is it just when it doesn't include you?
I'm getting in first.

657
00:52:49.002 --> 00:52:51.046
You're not getting
in the shower first. Hey!

658
00:52:51.129 --> 00:52:53.715
Oh. poor. beloved Anastasia.
the most famous woman on Earth

659
00:52:53.799 --> 00:52:56.093
- whose every word is cherished.
- My every word is given to me

660
00:52:56.176 --> 00:52:57.678
- by someone else!
- Who's waited on hand and foot.

661
00:52:57.761 --> 00:52:59.721
Whatever will she do if she
doesn't get to fly again. huh?

662
00:52:59.805 --> 00:53:02.808
- Oh. no. no. no. no. no.
- [straining] You're one to talk!

663
00:53:02.891 --> 00:53:05.644
All you do is… is… [breathing heavily]

664
00:53:40.053 --> 00:53:41.180
[exhales deeply]

665
00:54:32.147 --> 00:54:33.815
[Sergei speaking indistinctly]

666
00:54:34.608 --> 00:54:35.859
[security officer] Comrade Nikulov.

667
00:54:37.736 --> 00:54:38.737
Yes?

668
00:54:40.239 --> 00:54:41.490
You recognize this?

669
00:54:43.492 --> 00:54:44.493
[scoffs]

670
00:54:45.202 --> 00:54:47.204
Uh. <i>The Philosophy of a Common Task.</i>

671
00:54:50.666 --> 00:54:53.126
It was found during
a routine search of your residence.

672
00:54:54.294 --> 00:54:56.588
This kind of samizdat is forbidden.

673
00:54:56.672 --> 00:54:58.340
Yes. I'm… I'm aware. but…

674
00:54:58.423 --> 00:54:59.424
[sighs]

675
00:54:59.967 --> 00:55:02.177
…half of the engineers here
have read Fyodorov.

676
00:55:03.679 --> 00:55:05.013
Would you care to name them?

677
00:55:17.276 --> 00:55:18.277
Take him in.

678
00:55:21.363 --> 00:55:23.949
Uh. please. This is…
This is a misunderstanding. It's…

679
00:55:46.054 --> 00:55:49.057
[grunting]

680
00:56:24.843 --> 00:56:26.929
- Hi.
- I'm so sorry. I got caught up at work.

681
00:56:27.012 --> 00:56:28.764
Oh. my God. No. don't be silly.

682
00:56:28.847 --> 00:56:29.848
Come in.

683
00:56:31.475 --> 00:56:35.812
Zoya and I have had a nice long practice
and a quite tasty dinner. if I do say so.

684
00:56:35.896 --> 00:56:38.440
- [whispering] She's just in there.
- Oh. I don't doubt that.

685
00:56:40.859 --> 00:56:42.736
[whispering] Thank you
for taking care of her.

686
00:56:42.819 --> 00:56:43.862
No.

687
00:56:47.866 --> 00:56:50.410
Oh. no. Irinochka. please stay.
Let me make you some tea.

688
00:56:50.494 --> 00:56:52.496
I couldn't.
We've already put you out enough.

689
00:56:52.579 --> 00:56:53.747
Please stay.

690
00:56:56.750 --> 00:56:57.793
Black tea would be nice.

691
00:56:57.876 --> 00:56:59.086
[both laugh]

692
00:56:59.586 --> 00:57:00.671
Give me your coat.

693
00:57:06.927 --> 00:57:08.470
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

694
00:57:09.847 --> 00:57:11.014
[sighs]

695
00:57:13.100 --> 00:57:14.768
Your husband's not home?

696
00:57:14.852 --> 00:57:15.853
No.

697
00:57:16.937 --> 00:57:18.230
Valya's in Moscow.

698
00:57:19.147 --> 00:57:20.983
Some training thing.

699
00:57:21.817 --> 00:57:22.860
Or so he says.

700
00:57:24.987 --> 00:57:26.196
Where else would he be?

701
00:57:26.697 --> 00:57:28.532
Been asking myself the same thing.

702
00:57:43.172 --> 00:57:44.339
[sighs]

703
00:57:44.882 --> 00:57:46.133
I saw him with someone.

704
00:57:47.676 --> 00:57:48.677
A woman.

705
00:57:49.303 --> 00:57:50.721
When we were at The Philharmonic.

706
00:57:52.598 --> 00:57:54.266
He said he was going to the toilet.

707
00:57:54.975 --> 00:57:58.020
but I saw him huddled
together with her instead.

708
00:57:58.979 --> 00:58:01.064
[stammers] No.

709
00:58:02.733 --> 00:58:04.443
Valya would never be unfaithful to you.

710
00:58:04.526 --> 00:58:05.569
He adores you.

711
00:58:06.820 --> 00:58:07.946
You've never even met him.

712
00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:11.241
Well. no.

713
00:58:12.034 --> 00:58:13.619
Just from the way you talk of him.

714
00:58:14.786 --> 00:58:17.539
I'm… I'm sure he'd never do this.

715
00:58:17.623 --> 00:58:18.707
Maybe once.

716
00:58:19.583 --> 00:58:21.585
But we've just grown so distant lately.

717
00:58:22.920 --> 00:58:24.546
Especially since Paris.

718
00:58:28.175 --> 00:58:29.718
[inhales deeply]

719
00:58:29.801 --> 00:58:32.012
Have you ever been unfaithful to him?

720
00:58:36.183 --> 00:58:37.726
No. Never.

721
00:58:48.820 --> 00:58:49.821
[inhales deeply]

722
00:58:50.531 --> 00:58:52.366
Would you mind if I use the toilet?

723
00:58:52.449 --> 00:58:53.575
Of course not.

724
00:59:00.415 --> 00:59:02.084
[water flushing]

725
00:59:40.956 --> 00:59:42.124
[sighs]

726
00:59:45.627 --> 00:59:48.297
[tense music playing]

727
01:00:23.832 --> 01:00:26.835
[music intensifies]

728
01:00:27.305 --> 01:01:27.208
Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-
